'''John Truby''' (born 1952) is a [[screenwriter]], [[film director|director]] and [[screenwriting guru|screenwriting teacher]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ward |first=Lewis |authorlink= |title=Interview: John Truby on Screenwriting and Breaking In |publisher=[http://www.scriptmag.com/index.php Script Magazine] |date= |url=http://www.scriptmag.com/earticles/earticle.htm |accessdate=2007-07-31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702182835/http://www.scriptmag.com/earticles/earticle.htm |archivedate=2007-07-02 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> He has served as a consultant on over 1,000 film scripts over the past three decades, and is also known for the [[screenwriting software]] program Blockbuster (originally "Storyline Pro").
Truby argues that most [[screenwriting guru|teachers of screenwriting]] emphasize inner transformation of the characters but not the moral effect their actions have on others. He is critical of [[Syd Field|Syd Field's]] [[Screenwriting theories|three-act “Paradigm”]] and has instead crafted his own 22-step outline. Truby's first book ''The Anatomy of Story: 22 Steps to Becoming a Master Storyteller'' was published in October, 2007 by [[Faber and Faber]].<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0865479518 The Anatomy of Story: 22 Steps to Becoming a Master Storyteller] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5vOgcUsML?url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/0865479518 |date=31 December 2010 }}</ref>
==Screenwriting career== In the 1980s, Truby received his first credits, writing three episodes of [[21 Jump Street]]. He later received a co-writer credit on the 2011 Disney/BBC film ''[[African Cats]]''.<ref>{{IMDb name|0991399}}</ref>
